{{Notability|Places|date=March 2017}} [[File:FTC 3083 (6792597322).jpg|thumb|Modern day Dey Street]] '''Dey Street''' is a short street in [[Lower Manhattan]], in [[New York City]]. It passes the west side of the [[World Trade Center site#New buildings|World Trade Center site]] and the [[World Trade Center Transportation Hub]]. It runs for one block between [[Church Street (Manhattan)|Church Street]] and [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]. It originally ran to [[West Side Highway|West Street]], but the western reaches were demolished to make way for the World Trade Center in the late 1960s. It now extends to [[Greenwich Street]]. 15 Dey Street is the site of the first transcontinental telephone call.
== History == The origins of the streets name are rather ambiguous. It is possible that it was named after John Dies, who was in charge of building a fleet of batteaux for use against the French in 1755.
According to estimations made by map makers, Dey Street did not exist in 1742. It appears in a map dated to 1767, documented as ‘Dyes Street’. It reached from Broadway to Greenwich Street, which ran along the edge of the [[Hudson River]] at that time. As the island was built outward with landfill, the street gradually lengthened.
'''Dey's or Dies Dock. '''(M-L18) On the Hudson River at Dey Street, built in 1743.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldstreets.com/index.asp?letter=D|title=streets of new york|last=|first=|date=|website=oldstreets.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
'''Batteau or Battoe Street. '''(M-L18) The name refers to a type of boat used on inland waters. According to du Simitiere (1767), it was a commonly used name for what is now spelled Dey Street. In 1755 John Dies was in charge of building a fleet of batteaux for use against the French.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldstreets.com/index.asp?letter=B|title=streets of new york|last=|first=|date=|website=oldstreets.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
